{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12931"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12931"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.32,0.08,0.36,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5369"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12931"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62434"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"10997"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48067"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit at seven weeks\u0027 gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is originally from Syria but immigrated to Australia 25 years ago. She reports no symptoms of fatigue or shortness of breath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. No pallor, jaundice, or organomegaly is noted. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 97 g/L (120-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 65 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed blood cells: 5.3 \u00d7 10\u00b9\u00b2/L (4.2-5.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 6.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 250 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Silent carrier of \u237a thalassaemia","Alpha thalassaemia minor","Beta thalassaemia major","Iron deficiency anaemia","Dilutional anaemia of pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with asymptomatic microcytic anaemia and a normal RBC count, which is characteristic of thalassaemia trait. The high RBC count relative to the degree of anaemia (Mentzer Index \u0026lt;13) strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha thalassaemia minor\u003C/strong\u003E rather than iron deficiency, particularly given her Mediterranean origin where thalassaemia is prevalent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with low RBC count and symptoms when haemoglobin is this low. The Mentzer Index (MCV/RBC) would be \u0026gt;13, unlike in this case where it is approximately 12.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta thalassaemia major\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe condition presenting in infancy with failure to thrive, hepatosplenomegaly, and severe anaemia requiring regular transfusions. This patient\u0027s mild, asymptomatic presentation is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilent carrier of alpha thalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E (\u03b1-thalassaemia minima) results from deletion of one \u03b1-globin gene and produces no detectable haematological abnormalities. This patient\u0027s significant microcytic anaemia excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilutional anaemia of pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs later in pregnancy (peak at 24-26 weeks) and would not cause such a marked reduction in MCV. While some haemodilution may be present, the microcytosis indicates an underlying haemoglobinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of alpha vs beta thalassaemia trait requires haemoglobin electrophoresis or high-performance liquid chromatography. Genetic counselling should be offered as there are implications for the pregnancy if the partner is also a carrier.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thalassaemia trait typically presents with microcytic anaemia and normal to high RBC count, distinguishing it from iron deficiency anaemia.","The Mentzer Index (MCV/RBC) \u003C13 suggests thalassaemia, while \u003E13 suggests iron deficiency anaemia.","Patients with thalassaemia trait are often asymptomatic despite low haemoglobin levels."],"references":["Bain B. 2021 Guidelines For The Management of Transfusion Dependent Thalassaemia (TDT), Capellini MD, Farmakis D, Porter J and Taher A (Eds). Thalassaemia International Federation, 2021, ISBN\u201013 978\u20109963\u2010717\u201018\u20107. Available at: https://www.thalassemia.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/TIF-2021-Guidelines-for-Mgmt-of-TDT.pdf","Tan YL, Kidson-Gerber G. Antenatal haemoglobinopathy screening in Australia. Med J Aust. 2016;204(6):226-30. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.5694/mja15.01115?saml_referrer doi: 10.5694/mja15.01115","Tyrrell L, Rose G, Shukri A, Kahwash SB. Morphologic changes in red blood cells: An illustrated review of clinically important light microscopic findings. Malays J Pathol. 2021;43(2):219-39. Available at: http://www.mjpath.org.my/2021/v43n2/red-blood-cells.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62434"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12931"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62434"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:38:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T10:12:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5369"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76929"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type